Left multiplication can be computed by operating the rows of . Natrually, the properties of elementary matrices intrduce a lemma.

Lemma: Elementary matrices are invertible, and their inverses are also elementary matrices.

We give a story proof here: From the definitions, we know an elementary matrix is a linear operation over the rows of a matrix. Recall that linear operation is always invertible, and their inverses are also linear. So, the inverse of an elementary matrix is the inverse operation of these rows. addition becomes subtractive, swap changes its direction, and scaling factor becomes reciprocal. All of the inverse operations are linear (except 0), which is also an elementary matrix. By applying row reduction multiple times, we can solve linear equations. This method is called Gaussian elimination. which is suitable for computers.

This algorithm transforms the augmented matrix into row-echelon form (REF), allowing systematic solution of . The process comprises forward elimination and back substitution. Starting with the augmented matrix , process columns left to right. For each pivot column : - Pivot selection: Find the entry with largest absolute value in column at or below the current pivot row . Swap this row with row using a row-swap elementary matrix. - *Elimination: For each row , add a multiple of row to row to zero out entries below the pivot. Use row-replacement elementary matrices . - Scaling (optional for REF): Scale row to make the pivot 1 using .

The process continues until all pivot columns are processed, yielding an upper-triangular REF matrix.

1.4 Trace and Rank

We call the summation of diagonal elements the trace of a matrix. The most important thing of trace is related to eigenvalues. We will clarify in the following sections.

A set of vectors is linearly independent if implies . The rank of is the size of the largest linearly independent column subset. For an matrix , its columns represent vectors in . The rank is the maximum number of linearly independent columns—those that cannot be expressed as linear combinations of others. This value is bounded by due to dimensional constraints: at most vectors can be linearly independent in , and the matrix has only columns. This upper bound reflects the behavior of as a linear map . The rank equals the dimension of the image space (range) of . When the rank is strictly less than , the map is rank-deficient: if , the kernel (null space) is nontrivial; if , the map fails to span . For full-rank matrices (), square matrices are invertible, while rectangular matrices exhibit injectivity (full column rank) or surjectivity (full row rank).

2.2 Groups and Subgroups

A group is a set with a law of composition that has the following properties:

  • The law of composition is associative

  • Set contains an identity

  • Every element in has a inverse

If the law of composition is also commutative, it is called an Abelian group.

The order of group is the number of elements: For example, is a group, which only contains one element 0. Then the order of this group is 1. If the order is finite, is said to be a finite group. Otherwise, it is a infinite group.
